Three children were killed in Harry Gwala District following severe thunderstorms that hit parts of the KwaZulu-Natal province on Saturday afternoon. The KZN Department of Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs (Cogta) said the first incident that took place in the Dr Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma Local Municipality where a 10-year-old boy and a 15-year-old girl were swept away while trying to cross a local river in ward 12 in an area called Bethlehem. MEC for Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs, Sipho Hlomuka said in the second incident heavy rains and strong winds led a structural collapsed of a house. “In this incident one fatality was reported and its believed to be that of a child,” he said on Sunday. He said local disaster management teams have been dispatched to provide support to the affected families. “We call upon residents to exercise extreme caution as the province continues to experience inclement weather conditions. “Residents that have been affected by the inclement weather conditions are urged to contact their respective leadership at ward level so that adequate support can be provided,” said Hlomuka. He said disaster management teams are continuing with assessments of areas that were affected by the storm.